Name: Gabriel, Francis, photographer
Title: Railway Goods Yards
Description: Photograph  14.5 cm x 19.9 cm;RESERVE 4 [glass plate negative]
Summary: [General description] The busy railway goods yards with goods shed, locomotives, rolling stock and horse drawn wagons, loaded with firewood and bricks. On the extreme right a locomotive steams past some bogey wagons full of bricks which a man is unloading, one by one, into his horse drawn wagon. Several of the horses are taking a break, eating from nosebags. [On back of photograph] 'Railway Goods Yards /  North Terrace, west of Morphett St. / Acres 6 and 7 in background / 1903-09 / On the left is the Black Swan Hotel, the near side of which is 1171/2 yards west of Morphett Street. The part of North Terrace obscured by the smoke of the engine is about 65 yds. East of George Street.'
Subject: Horse drawn vehicles -- South Australia -- Adelaide;Black Swan Hotel (Adelaide, S. Aust.);Railroads -- South Australia -- Adelaide;Railroads -- Rolling stock

Title: North Terrace, Adelaide, looking West
Summary: [General description] A lady in full Edwardian dress trips across the North Terrace- King William Street intersection. Houses of Parliament are on the right, hotels on the left and traffic is still mostly horse-drawn  only one car in sight.  Horse cabs are standing in the centre of the road waiting for business, framed by utility wires which cross the intersection of North Terrace and King William Street.  The three storey building with verandahs on the left is the iconic South Australian Hotel. [On back of photograph] 'North Terrace, looking west from King William Street. / c. 1908'

Title: Stephens Place, Adelaide

The house on the extreme right, which  belonged to Doctor Campbell, is soon to be demolished to make way for the second stage. See B 1826, taken in 1915, for a view of the completed Verco Building. The right side of the two storey building at the left of the photograph is 34 yards south of North Terrace. For an earlier view of the premises on the left, see B 2488

Name: Gabriel, Francis, photographer
Title: North Terrace, Adelaide
Summary: North Terrace, Adelaide, on the corner of Stephens Place, showing the Verco Building. This was built for Dr William Alfred Verco, physician and developer. The architect, Eric H McMichael, was married to Constance Verco. This was his first commission, and it set him on the path to a successful career. This photo was taken soon after its completion. The frontage of the building is 17 yards. Next door, on the right, is the old Liberal Union building. A horse and buggy and a motor car are parked outside. See B 2253 for a view of the new building under construction in 1924

Name: Gabriel, Francis, photographer
Title: Verco Building, Adelaide
Summary: Verco Building, one of Adelaide's earliest skyscrapers, on the corner of North Terrace, and Stephens Place. This view was taken soon after the completion of its second stage. Subject: Buildings -- South Australia -- Adelaide

Summary: [General description] Ruthven Mansions on Pulteney Street is under construction, surrounded by scaffolding of long wooden poles tethered together with rope. A man in a bowler hat poses for the photographer in front of the building and various tradesmen pose on the scaffolding and amongst the roof timbers, including one man perched atop the unfinished cupola. Piles of builders sand and metal are heaped in front of the site. A sign reads Ruthven Mansions Residential Flats in course of erection for R.F. Ruthven Smith Esq. Architects Black and Fuller. Contractors A.R. Maddern and Son. Particulars, Rentals etc. Please apply Fenn and Hardy, Solicitors, 72 King William Street. [On back of photograph] 'Acres 24 and 39 / Pulteney Street, west side, north of Rundle Street / about 1911 / Left side of building is 42 yards north of Rundle St. /  Frontage of new building : 27 yards.'
Subject: Apartment houses -- South Australia -- Adelaide;Ruthven Mansions (Adelaide. S. Aust.)

Title: North Terrace, Adelaide

Right side of gate is 64 yards west of Tavistock Street.'[General description]  Designed by William McMinn in 1881, this Italianate style two storey townhouse features a mansard roof with wrought iron cresting. The view was taken from the opposite side of North Terrace, with a wrought iron fence in the foreground

Name: Gall, Ernest, photographer
Title: Adelaide, South Australia, from the Adelaide Hospital
Summary: View of Adelaide from the Adelaide Hospital looking south west across North Terrace toward Chalmers Church, later renamed Scots Church. The Adelaide Town Hall and Post Office clock towers are visible to the left and the Exhibition building is the tallest building on the right.

Title: Trams, Old and New in North Terrace, Adelaide
Summary: [General description] The end of one era and the beginning of another. Two trams stand together, on the right a horse tram, soon to be defunct, on the left a new electric tram. [On back of photograph] 'Acre 28 / North Terrace, south side, looking east from Frome Road / 1909'
Subject: Horse tramways -- South Australia -- Adelaide;Trams -- South Australia -- Adelaide

Name: Gabriel, Francis, photographer
Title: Horse trams old and new, North Terrace, Adelaide
Summary: [General description] Two horse trams, standing side by side. One is the old horse drawn type, with its well turned out driver and matching pair of horses, the other is the new electric tram. North Terrace road and buildings form a backdrop. In the foreground is an ornate tram pole. [On back of photograph] 'Acre 28 / North Terrace, looking east from Frome Road / c. 1909'
Subject: Horse tramways -- South Australia -- Adelaide;Trams -- South Australia -- Adelaide

Title: Cottage, George Street, Adelaide
Summary: Small cottage and front garden, George Street, now called Vaughan Place, off the north side of Rundle Street east, Adelaide.  Erected about 1840.  Residence of E.W. Hitchin, Auditor General, John Richards, MP, and the birthplace of the Hon. Crawford Vaughan.  Demolished between 1914- 1923.  Turner's bakehouse erected on the site.  The lane between the two houses is 50 yards north of Rundle Street

Name: McGann, photographer
Title: Foy & Gibson's department store

Subject: Foy & Gibson Limited;Department stores -- Adelaide -- South Australia

Name: Gall, Ernest, photographer
Title: Rundle Street
Summary: [General description] Small shops along the northern side of Rundle Street, east of Pulteney Street. They include a clothing store, R. Jacobs Leather House, The London Bazaar, J. Brandwood Cycle and Motor Engineers and G.D. Roberts Hairdressers. Two men and two women are talking outside the cycle shop. The shop windows are full of goods and some display their wares on the footpath. [On back of photograph] Acre 38. Rundle Street, north side. 1909-10. Probably 1909. See B 7787/16. Right side of Brandwood's is 35 yards east of Pulteney Street

Name: Gall, Ernest, photographer
Title: Rundle Street
Summary: [General description] Shops along Rundle Street, east of Pulteney Street. The shops include the Victoria Dye Works and Cleaners sharing with G.D. Roberts Hairdressers. A poster outside the hairdressers advertises a theatre production of "The Merry Widow." Next door at number 174 stands E. Warhurst's Musical Instruments. Mrs. A. Popp, later A. Renof, Fruiterer has a large display of fruit in her York Fruit Palace. A.E. Jory Watchmakers is situated at number 178 Rundle Street.  [On back of photograph] Acre 38. Rundle Street, north side. 1909-10. Probably 1909. See B 7787/16. Left side of Victoria Dye Works is 35 yards east of Pulteney street. The dyeworks and No. 174 were demolished between 1928 and 1932 and were replaced by the eastern portion of Craven's Building (next door to the Savings Bank) Compare with B 6200

Name: Gall, Ernest, photographer
Title: Rundle Street
Summary: [General description] Craven and Armstrong Building on the corner of Rundle Street and Pulteney Street. Women shoppers are appraising clothing in Craven and Armstrong Importers Store. The Leather House stands next door to this building in Rundle Street. The buildings adjoining Craven and Armstrong in Pulteney Street include Dining Rooms and W.C.T.U. and Fearn and Company. Hoopers Pianos are nearer North Terrace. The Exhibition Building can be seen in the distance on North Terrace. The tram line runs along Pulteney Street. [On back of photograph] Acre 38. North east corner of Rundle Street and Pulteney Streets. 1909-10. Probably 1909. See B 7787/16. Near side of Fearn's premises (on the left) is 41 and a half yards north of Rundle Street. Extreme right is about 33 yards east of Pulteney Street

Name: Gall, Ernest, photographer
Title: Rundle Street

At number 184 is the premises of McNeill's Photographers and Art Framers. [On back of photograph] Acre 38. Rundle Street, north side. 1909-12. Probably 1909. See B 7787/16. Summary: Rundle Street, Adelaide, north side. A crowd of well-dressed people, some of the ladies with sun umbrellas, have turned out for the John Martin's sale. On the right is Charles Street. The left side of John Martin's (No. 98) is 42 yards west of Charles Street. The three story building on the left was burned down on April 6 1901, [see BRG 121/1/598] after which the two story portion was demolished to make way for the new premises, and the Magic Cave was excavated. Name: Gabriel, Francis, photographer
Title: Hindley Street, Adelaide
Summary: Grant's Coffee Palace, Hindley street, Adelaide. Designed by architect Albert Selmar Conrad, and built in 1903, the Austral Stores originally comprised 12 shops and dwellings. After 1908 the building operated as Grant's Coffee Palace, a 'coffee palace' being a popular alternative to hotels after the growth of the temperance movement. In 1919 it was taken over by John West, and has been known as West's Coffee Palace ever since. The paired and turreted towers, projecting gables, red brick and render walls, Byzantine details and steep terracotta tiled roof are characteristic of the Federation period. Right side of Grant's is 36 yards west of Victoria Street and frontage is 62.5 yards. For views taken in 1960, see B 14327-29
Subject: West's Coffee Palace (Adelaide, S. Aust.);Architecture, Edwardian -- South Australia -- Adelaide

Title: House, Hindley Street, Adelaide
Summary: Hindley Street, Adelaide, south side, next door (east) to the West End Brewery.  The photo was taken January 23rd 1914.   The right side of the house is 30 yards west of George Street. Built by William Collins in 1838 or 1839, it was demolished between 1914 & 1923 and the site was used as a yard by Harley & Co., ironfoundries. Former occupants include Dr. J.N. Knott (1843) and later by the Rev. J.A. Dowie, founder of Zion City.  More recently was occupied by Veterinary Surgeon, R.S. Crabb. (see Observer, April 8, 1905, p.23)

Name: Gall, Ernest, photographer
Title: Rundle Street, Adelaide
Summary: [General description] Two gentlemen are standing in front of the Hamburg Hotel. The building features decorative wooden verandah brackets and iron lace, and a large mirror by the front door advertises Wolfe's Schnapps. The licensee at this time was Jno. H. Flannagan. The hotel started out as the Suffolk Inn in 1840, but was known as the Hamburg since 1847. From 1915-1966, when it was de-licenced, it was named the Oriental. See B 1203 for a view of the hotel, virtually unchanged in 1923, and one taken in 1964, (B 15320), showing many alterations. [On back of photograph] 'Acre 82 / Hamburg Hotel / Rundle Street, east corner of Gawler Place / 1909'

The new hotel was renamed the Grand Central and the licensee in 1913 was W.H. Messenger. Foy & Gibsons' Rundle Street frontage is 91 yards. The Pulteney Street frontage of the Grand Central Hotel is 40 yards. For alterations made to the verandah in 1938, see B 7440

Title: King William Street, Adelaide
Summary: King William Street, Adelaide, east side. The right side of the Clarence Hotel is 46 yards north of Pirie Street and its frontage is 15 yards. The Tivoli Theatre is advertised with decorative lights. Several men, possibly staff and patrons, are posing in front of the building. For a view of the hotel taken in 1925, see B 2450. The Clarence Hotel started out as the Alma Shades in 1857, then in 1858, was known as the Adelaide Shades. It was re-named as the Clarence Hotel from 1863-1917 and then became the Majestic. It traded under that name until 1981 when it was demolished

Title: King William Street, Adelaide

Summary: [General description] Two of the new electric trams, numbers 42 to Hyde Park and 59 to Edward Street, Kensington. The tram lines and poles that support the wires recede into the distance. City buildings line the streets, the most prominent being the Town Hall with its empty clock face. Two men with bowler hats stroll along the middle of the road. [On back of photograph] 'King William Street, looking south from a point south of Grenfell Street / Dec. 1909 / Extreme right is 63 yards north of Waymouth Street.' Name: Gabriel, Francis, photographer
Title: Waymouth Street, Adelaide
Description: Photograph  20.1 cm x 15.6 cm;RESERVE 4 [glass plate negative]
Summary: [General description] This three storey brick building is the premises of A.M. Bickford & Sons. Two of the firm's horse drawn delivery wagons are proudly posed in front of the building. On one of the wagons is an advertisement for Maltox, "The tonic drink for all". Advertisements for Bickford's "Our Jack" brand, featuring a kookaburra with the words "sign of quality" are displayed on the building. William Bickford, a chemist, arrived in South Australia in 1839 and established the first druggist in Hindley Street. Upon his death in 1850 his wife, Ann Margaret continued the business which later became A.M. Bickford & Sons in 1871. In 1874 Bickford's bought a cordial factory in Waymouth Street and the family firm still flourishes today (2009), trading as Bickfords Australia. [On back of photograph] 'Acre 175 / Waymouth Street, north side / may 1916 / Frontage: 13.5 yards. Near side is 11 yards east of Young Street.'
Subject: A.M. Bickford & Sons;Horse drawn vehicles -- South Australia -- Adelaide

Title: Gilles Arcade, Adelaide
Description: Photograph  19.4 cm x 14.3 cm;RESERVE 4 [glass plate negative]
Summary: Old Victoria Theatre, Gilles Arcade, Adelaide.  It was built in 1842 and opened under the name 'The Queens' Theatre'.  In 1843 the building became South Australia's first Law Courts, then it was refurbished and became the Royal Victoria Theatre' and operated under this name from 1850-1868.  After many years of non-theatrical use it was converted back into a theatre again in 1996.  Shannon's premises (the old theatre) face north.  The door on the right leading to Shannon's office is 95 yards east of Light Square.  Shannon's frontage is 78 yards south of Currie Street

Summary: [General description] Two of the new electric trams, numbers 44 and 50, are seen on King William Street, with tram tracks and the poles that support the wires prominent in the foreground. Title: Maughan Church, Franklin St, Adelaide
Summary: [General description] The prominent tower of the Maughan Church is seen silhouetted against the sky. Designed by architect James Macgeorge, this bluestone church was built in 1866 and known as the Methodist New Connexion Church. It was later named the Maughan Church after its pioneering minister, James Maughan. This spire was a landmark until the demolition and subsequent replacement of the church circa 1965. The Victoria Building, corner Flinders St. & Victoria Square, was bought from the estate of the late T.C.Bray by S.A.Govt. in financial year 1908-9. See L.T.O. Records and S.A. Parliamentary Paper 1911-12, no. 29, page 82, entry 'Adelaide, Victoria Building'. Various government departments moved into Victoria Building over the next few years, and in 1910 it was used by the Department of Agriculture. Summary: [On back of photograph] 'St. Patrick's Church, Grote Street / Acres 319 & 319 / March 1914 / (Photo by Krischock) / Frontage: 23 yards / Right side is 17 yards west of Burton Avenue. Left side is 133 yards east of West Terrace.' [General description] A priest can be seen standing inside the doorway of this newly completed church, seen in three quarter view. Outside a woman tends to a baby in a large perambulator. Designed by Woods Bagot  the church was dedicated on 15 March, 1914. It was said to be inspired by the Church of the Holy Spirit in Florence and the design, based on a basilica, originally included a sacristy and dome. However a combination of insufficient funds and the outbreak of World War 1meant that the project remained unfinished

Name: Gabriel, Francis, photographer
Title: Moore Street, Adelaide
Description: Negative (glass, half plate)  16.5 cm x 12.1 cm;RESERVE 4
Summary: Moore Street, Adelaide, east side, in May 1912. The subject is St. Mary Magdalene's Mission church, taken just before the St Peter's College Mission was built on the site of the cottage next door. This church was established in Moore Street in 1886, using the materials from the original St John's in the Wilderness of Halifax Street, built in the 1840s. Known as St John's Mission Church, lt later [1905] became known as the parish church of St Mary Magdalene. The far side of the church is 56 yards north of Carrington Street, and Cook's Place is 30.5 yards north of Carrington Street. See B 2148 for a view taken in November 1912, showing the new Mission

Title: Motor vehicle accident
Summary: Accident involving a 20-25h.p. Fiat motor car, registration number 16, at the intersection of Jeffcott and Ward Streets at about 7.00pm on 13 April 1911. Driven by its owner, Charles Gilbert, the car hired by Sylvia Maurer, Evelyn (Evie) Aborn and Vi Martin from the Gay Gordons Theatre Company was returning from the Outer Harbor when it crashed into a trench at the intersection. In June 1911 Miss Aborn who suffered the most severe injuries sued F.A. McCarty & Co., for failing to adequately light the trench. She was awarded 450 Pound.
Subject: Traffic accidents -- South Australia -- North Adelaide;Fiat automobile;Automobiles -- South Australia -- North Adelaide;Taxicabs -- South Australia

Title: View from the North Adelaide parklands
Summary: View from the North Adelaide parklands looking south. Chas. Gerner's business is visible in the middle ground, with St Peter's Cathedral in the distance. According to a researcher, this image depicts the location near the corner of King William Road and Brougham Place, which is approximately one kilometre north from the corner of Tynte Street and Lefevre Terrace. The building on the left is now part of the Adelaide Children's Hospital Incorporated buildings. It is called the Angus Building now, and dates from 1893. Further south, part of the Alan Campbell Building is in view also part of what is now the Women's and Chidren's Hospital. The current Cathedral Hotel can be seen further south, on the corner of Kermode Street.

This cottage had a galvanised roof [the original shingles can be seen], but it was taken off just before the photo was taken. Afterwards, it was either demolished or was added to in front so as to bring the verandah to within approximately a yard of the footpath. The right side of the cottage is 61 yards north of Archer street

Name: Gall, Ernest, photographer
Title: Residence of Doctor Clement Armour Verco at North Adelaide
Summary: The Residence of Doctor Clement Armour Verco on the corner of Tynte Street North Adelaide. The house is located on the south side of Tynte Street and on the eastern corner of Centenary Street. The near side of house is eighty yards east of O'Connell Street. The imposing two storey sandstone building has a return verandah on both levels. Doctor Verco, a medical practitioner, was resident here from 1906 to 1910. [On back of photograph] Acre 831 Tynte Street, south side. 1906. East corner of Centenary Street. Near side of house is 80 yards east of O'Connell Street

Summary: [General description] Looking east down Stanley Street near the intersection with Lefevre Terrace. Houses are seen receding towards the distant foothills. Substantial houses and gardens of the well-off appear in the foreground. Compare with B 3474, a similar view taken in 1910. This photograph is the right side of a panorama comprising B 3477 - B 3479. [On back of photograph] 'Stanley St. looking east / Taken from the North Adelaide Congregational Church / Acres 1027, 1025, 1024' (Another hand) 'About 1904. On the left is Lefevre Terrace. Near side of house in foreground is 54 yards west of Lefevre Terrace.' (Another hand) 'Steep hill behind these houses'
Subject: Panoramas -- South Australia -- North Adelaide;North Adelaide -- Buildings, structures, etc

Name: Gabriel, Francis, photographer
Title: Stanley Street, North Adelaide
Summary: Stanley Street, North Adelaide, north side, in December 1916. Lawson's Store is a two storey building which features an unusual flagstaff, accessed by a ladder from its first floor balcony. This was taken down before 1924. A large advertisement for Lion Brand Groceries is displayed on its balcony. The left side of the shop is 90 yards north east of West Pallant Street. See B 14283 for a view of this building taken in 1960
Subject: Stores, Retail -- South Australia -- Adelaide
